# Test Repo Isolation

**NEVER** run tests, smoke tests, or any validation scripts against a real repository (e.g. anything under `~/youidev/`, `~/Desktop/<project>/`, or any repo the user has open).

## Always Do This

Create a throwaway repo in `/tmp` using `mkdtempSync` or a shell `mktemp -d`, seed it with commits, then delete it on exit:

```ts
import { mkdtempSync, rmSync } from 'node:fs'
import { tmpdir } from 'node:os'
import { execSync } from 'node:child_process'

function makeTestRepo(): string {
  const dir = mkdtempSync(`${tmpdir()}/simplegit-test-`)
  const git = (cmd: string) =>
    execSync(`git ${cmd}`, { cwd: dir, stdio: 'pipe' })
  git('init -q')
  git('config user.email "test@simplegit.dev"')
  git('config user.name "Test User"')
  git('config commit.gpgsign false')   // required — system may have GPG signing on
  // ... seed commits, tags, branches as needed
  return dir
}

const REPO = makeTestRepo()
process.on('exit', () => rmSync(REPO, { recursive: true }))
```

## Never Do This

```ts
// ❌ Using the project root (not a git repo anyway)
const REPO = process.cwd()

// ❌ Using any path from the user's real work
const REPO = '/Users/chris.ziraldo/youidev/some-project'
const REPO = `${os.homedir()}/Desktop/SomeApp`
```

## GPG Note

The user's git is configured to GPG-sign commits. Always set `commit.gpgsign false` in any test repo, otherwise commits will fail with `gpg: signing failed`.
